etymologies: late Middle English; earliest use found in Geoffrey Chaucer (c1340–1400), poet and administrator. Partly from homage + -er, and partly from Anglo-Norman homager person who owes homage

definitions: A person who shows reverence, dutiful respect, or honour to another; a worshipper.
A person who owes homage or fealty; one who holds land by homage.

notes.text: crown, liege homager: see the first element.

definitions: A manorial tenant, especially one attending a manorial court, or the jury of such a court. Compare "homage".
